TY  - JOUR
TI  - Team Incentives and Performance: Evidence from a Retail Chain
AU  - Friebel, Guido
AU  - Heinz, Matthias
AU  - Krueger, Miriam
AU  - Zubanov, Nikolay
AB  - [In a field experiment with a retail chain (1,300 employees, 193 shops), randomly selected sales teams received a bonus. The bonus increases both sales and number of customers dealt with by 3 percent. Each dollar spent on the bonus generates $3.80 in sales, and $2.10 in profit. Wages increase by 2.2 percent while inequality rises only moderately. The analysis suggests effort complementarities to be important, and the effectiveness of peer pressure in overcoming free-riding to be limited. After rolling out the bonus scheme, the performance of the treatment and control shops converges, suggesting long-term stability of the treatment effect.]
